article.headline: Strom and teammates prove themselves in easy victory

images.name: Andersson_Kadidja 010603 Inline
images.caption: Kadidja Andersson pulls down a rebound for Minnesota, but the Golden Gophers were struggling most of the night.

article.linkText: Off bench, Strom helps No. 14 Penn State beat No. 10 Minnesota
article.story:
STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Jess Strom wasn't happy about starting
a game on the bench for the first time in her career.

<photo1>

	   Still, she responded by tying her career-high with 20 points and
adding eight assists as Penn State (No. 14 ESPN/USA Today; No. 17 Associated Press) posted a 83-53 upset of Minnesota (No. 10 ESPN/USA Today; No. 9 Associated Press).

	   ''Kelly (Mazzante) said before the game, 'Just don't let us
down,' '' Strom said. ''And they're my best friends -- I wasn't
going to let them down.''

	   Truth be told, Strom wasn't the only one upset coming into the
game. Penn State (11-3, 2-0 Big Ten) was embarrassed by its nationally televised 80-63 defeat at Louisiana State on Saturday and came
into the game feeling it needed to prove itself.

	   Penn State did just that, handing the Golden Gophers (12-1, 1-1) their
first defeat and holding one of the nation's highest-scoring teams to
its lowest offensive output of the season.

	   ''I'll be very honest, I was not the most pleasant person for
the 48 hours between those games,'' Penn State coach Rene Portland
said. ''I was angry. I was embarrassed. I didn't feel we
represented ourselves or the university or the commitment we've
made in the way we played at LSU.''

	   Penn State didn't start the game Monday much better, as both teams
struggled offensively early in the first half.

	   But with the game tied at 17, the Lady Lions went on a 10-0 run,
taking a 27-17 lead with 4:20 left in the half. Mazzante hit a
3-pointer in the run, then started scoring from all over, in
transition, knocking down 3-pointers, fading away on the baseline
and using a baby hook in the paint.

	   Mazzante finished with 22 points, 17 of them in the first half.

	   ''We didn't want to focus so much on her that we let the other
players beat us,'' said Minnesota coach Pam Borton, whose team held
Mazzante to just five points until 6:15 remained in the first half.
''Once she starts getting into a flow and has even a half-second to
look at the basket, she's going to make those shots.''

	   Penn State opened the second half on a 19-5 run, taking a 61-28
lead on Strom's fastbreak layup with 13:20 left. The Gophers never
seemed to adjust to Penn State's switching defenses and made just
18 of 56 shots -- including just two of 13 from 3-point range.

	   ''They changed defense quickly. We completely got out of our
tempo and didn't push the ball up the floor,'' Borton said. ''We
got away from playing team basketball.''

	   Tanisha Wright scored 17 points for Penn State, Jessica Brungo
11 and Ashli Schwab 10.

	   Lindsay Whalen had 22 points for Minnesota.

	   Penn State led 42-23 at halftime, the fewest points
Minnesota has scored in an opening half this season. Its previous
low was 29 points against Northern Iowa.
